    From the manufacturer

    Description

    ScanWatch 2 hybrid smart watch provides robust health insights round-the-clock. This newest generation offers new and exclusive sensors, including the TempTech24/7 module which for the first time, delivers day & night body temperature variation tracking, alongside proactive heart health notifications, AFib detection* via a 1L ECG, and blood oxygen levels. These cutting-edge sensors effortlessly support your healthy lifestyle and is the perfect fitness tracker and heart rate monitor and step counter. ScanWatch 2 also features its trademark sleep and activity tracking plus Withings iconic 30-day battery life before needing to be recharged. *Available via Withings Scan Monitor

    Features & details

    Features

    • ELECTROCARDIOGRAM - Get a medical grade ECG. Smartwatch heart rate monitor detects atrial fibrillation or normal heart rhythm in 30 seconds with ECG via Withings Scan Monitor.
    • PROACTIVE HEART HEALTH TRACKING - 24/7 heart rate monitoring with notifications if your heart rate is too high or too low. Overnight heart rate variability so you can track heart health over time.
    • 24/7 TEMPERATURE TRACKING - Using our breakthrough TempTech24/7 module, get baseline body temp and fluctuations that may indicate the onset of illness. Boost your workout via temp variation zones.
    • ADVANCED RESPIRATORY INSIGHTS - Measure your blood oxygen level on-demand (SpO2) and track overnight for breathing disturbances.
    • SLEEP TRACKER - Track a variety of sleep measurements: sleep duration, time spent in light sleep & deep sleep, sleep interruptions, sleep regularity, and a Sleep Quality Score assessment.

    • Gabriel's Buddy
      4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Best choice for me - More health, less phone in my life.
      Reviewed in the United States on February 2, 2025
      Style: ScanWatch 2 - 42mmColor: Black
      I love the look of the traditional watch and its ability to track my health data. Part of my overall health kick is to get less involved with my phone, so it's nice to be able to look at the time or start an exercise without being distracted by other things. It's... See more
      I love the look of the traditional watch and its ability to track my health data. Part of my overall health kick is to get less involved with my phone, so it's nice to be able to look at the time or start an exercise without being distracted by other things. It's hard to express just how perfect this is. I choose to get call notifications, but I turn off general notifications. All communication between the phone and watch is one-way, so no responding, music controls, etc.

      The step tracking, heart rate, and Sp02 seem right on. It lasts for about 2 to 3 weeks for me, which is great because I wear it all the time and so have my sleep tracking (including level, heart rate, and SpO2) and 24-hour hear tracking. I use the EKG once a week or and it seems to work well, but I'm not sure of its value other than occasionally. Temperature is included as a "delta" from the average value and it's interesting to see the differences when exercising or sleeping.

      I think it claims 30 days, which I'm not getting, and which is the main reason for 4 stars. I don't think I'm doing anything excessive, although I do track hear rate and I use the workout feature (stationary bicycling) about 3 hours a week. It also doesn't have it's own GPS, so if you want to track an outdoor walking or biking workout, you need to bring your phone. It uses the phone's GPS, which seems well integrated once you have the location sharing settings all in place.

      I have a scale and blood pressure cuff from the same manufacturer and it's great to have all the things in the same place. My doctor had a question the last visit and having blood pressure history helped us make a choice about my health options. The connected scale is good too and nice to have this all in one place.

      I don't have many complaints - there is what seems to be a "seconds" subdial, which is really a step goal tracker. Once around is your goal (set via the app). It would be nice to be able to make this a legitimate seconds hand or, even better, and overall activity tracker that would show progress to other things. I don't really care about my step goal on days I'm on the bike for an hour, for example. I just want the overall activity (similar to Googe Fit "Heart Points" based on heart rate, duration, and activities). Alternately it might be good to have a longer term trending health score - some measure to show my sleep/blood pressure/activity level, etc. are all in a good zone. There are measures for these on the app, from 0 to 100, and maybe just nice to put these on the subdia. But not a big deal.

      It integrates with my workout apps through Android "Health Connect", which works well (for example, I can see heart rate from my watch in the Google Fit app), but if I use my watch and my workout app (e.g Zwift/Strava) to monitor a workout, I can sometimes get duplicate workouts in the app.

    • SB
      2.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Good watch, but my piece was defective
      Reviewed in the United States on January 11, 2024
      Style: ScanWatch 2 - 38mmColor: RoseGold
      I have owned two previous generations of the Withings Watch series. The Nokia Steel HR, and the Withings Smartwatch. I couldn't be happier with those watches. They have the functionality that make smartwatches useful without the unnecessary bells and whistles that turn... See more
      I have owned two previous generations of the Withings Watch series. The Nokia Steel HR, and the Withings Smartwatch. I couldn't be happier with those watches. They have the functionality that make smartwatches useful without the unnecessary bells and whistles that turn them into a smartphone strapped to your wrist. The battery lasts weeks, and the watch feels solid like a traditional analog watch - the type you would wear for years and it would keep ticking along.

      So when the new Scanwatch 2 was announced, I decided to get an upgrade. From a functionality standpoint, it is an upgrade. The temperature sensor is great - it warns you of changes in your average temperature. The concept is brilliant - if you are about to come down with something and are alerted of this by your watch then you could preemptively take it easy - cancel workouts and appointments and maybe try to avoid the full force of the cold/flu etc. The rest is about the same with a general feel of fine tuning.

      Unfortunately, two days after wearing the watch, without any events (falls etc.) the crown stopped working. Pressing the crown would not turn the screen on as it should. I tried resetting the watch, updating the firmware, re-paring it with my phone but the issue appeared to be a real defect in the watch.

      I tried contacting Withings support. The website said that reps were available over chat, but clicking on chat just made you wait indefinitely - hours and nobody showed up. I could request a phone appointment, but the next appointment I could book was a month later.

      I posted in Withings online forum about my problem, expressing a willingness to help debug the issue. But I did not get a response. Moreover, I found complaints of the same problem by other customers that had gone months without an answer. Why a company would run an online forum for customers to post problems and leave it unattended is beyond me.

      Anyway, from my experience I concluded that the newest generation is not getting the love that the previous generations did.

      I purchased this watch to replace (but really join) the simpler version. My first one did not calculate my oxygen saturation or do ECG. I was VERY pleasantly surprised at the actual beauty of the watch itself (I purchased the rose gold version). Im really loving the color. As for the functions included with this version, it is much more detailed. The heart rate function is the one I use the most as I have a heart condition that this watch helps me keep an eye on. I have finally gotten to where I can actually get a reading instead of getting INCONCLUSIVE! It was a bit frustrating at first but I get that message far less now.

      This watch has replaced my Apple Watch as this one seems to be more what I need to keep track of my health. It will give notifications for low heart rate & high heart rate and Im sure other functions send notifications as well. I just havent needed other ones at this point. One thing I have noticed with this edition is that when you go into the functions to check things, the hands literally move to the 10:10 position so they do not block the readout screen. I did have difficulty seeing through the hands on the other watch. As soon as you exit the functions the hands go back to the current time. This only happens if the time of day is at a time when the hands are obstructing the functions screen.

      All in all Im VERY GLAD that I purchased this watch!
